`crates/steno/src/expand/infinite/` is the programmatic-lookup alternative to full enumeration: it builds two lookup tables (types, constructs) from Pass A output and replays type-filling on demand via an obligation-stack walker, keeping expansion cost proportional to strokes pressed rather than exponential in stroke count. Depending on this subtree gets you `build_tables` (construction), `walk` (runtime replay), and `emit_data_header`/`emit_test_header` (C++ header generation for javelin-ext).

The cross-cutting contract is the D12 slot-fill order and `%t` template format defined in `mod.rs`'s `InfType`/`Construct` records: `walk.rs`'s `render_type`/`template_fragments` consume that exact representation to reproduce what `build-javelin`'s C++ replay independently emits, so any change to slot ordering or template markers must move together across `mod.rs` and `walk.rs`, and downstream must stay byte-identical to the C++ side. Fuse handling is a second shared thread — `mod.rs` detects stroke-level fuse collisions at build time (`check_fuse_ambiguity`), while `walk.rs` scores fused constructs higher by specificity at runtime; both must agree on what counts as a fused base.

`mod.rs` is the table builder and single source of truth for `InfType`/`Construct` shapes; `walk.rs` is the runtime consumer that never panics on malformed input, returning `None` instead; `emit/` is the C++-facing output layer, itself split into real dictionary data (`data.rs`) versus a golden-test fixture (`test.rs`, fed by `sample.rs`) that pins `walk`'s behavior — the fixture can drift in coverage from the dictionary without breaking the build, since the two emit paths are independently maintained.

No intent.md is present, so no divergence check is possible.